1 Setup

  • CRC paper actually used both training and validation datasets (total of 18) for Figure 4. Fig4C_CMSvs.R and Fig4C_contScores.R scripts are using only 10 validation datasets. If you want to use all 18 datasets, block the line 11-13 of those scripts.
## line 11-13
# load("data/eSets/trainingSetNames.RData")
# validationSetNames <- setdiff(setNames, trainingSetNames)
# setNames <- validationSetNames

  • Fig4C_CMSvs.R script requires three environmental variables set before running: m2_name (column name for the model to be compared to CMS), m2_1 and m2_2 (names of the two model variables that form the group to be compared to CMS)

  • Fig4C_contScores.R script requires six environmental variables set before running: m1_name, m1_1, m1_2 for one model, m2_name, m2_1, m2_2 for the other.

2 Compare to CMS

2.1 CMS vs. PCSS1/2

m2_name <- "PCSS"
m2_1 <- "PCSS1"
m2_2 <- "PCSS2"
source("R/Fig4C_CMSvs.R", print.eval = TRUE)

2.2 CMS vs. PCcluster1575/834

PCcluster1575/834 are the most similar PCclsuters to PCSS1/2, respectively, based on Pearson correlation.

m2_name <- "RAV"
m2_1 <- "PCcluster1575"
m2_2 <- "PCcluster834"
source("R/Fig4C_CMSvs.R", print.eval = TRUE)
## Warning: Removed 46 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).
## Warning: Removed 46 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

2.3 CMS vs. PCcluster834/833

PCcluster834/833 have the largest r-squared score when we compared the samples scores against the metadata, CMS.

m2_name <- "RAV"
m2_1 <- "PCcluster834"
m2_2 <- "PCcluster833"
